3. Method
3.1. Preliminaries
Diffusion models [26, 47, 18] are denoising models that iteratively restore data x0 from its Gaussian noise corruption xT with a total step number T . Such a restoration process is usually known as the reverse diffusion process pŒ∏(xt‚àí1|xt) and the opposite of the reverse process is the forward diffusion process that blends the signal with noise q(xt|xt‚àí1):
q(xt|xt‚àí1) = N (xt; 1 ‚àí Œ≤txt‚àí1; Œ≤tI)

pŒ∏(xt‚àí1|xt) = N (xt‚àí1; ¬µŒ∏(xt, t); Œ£Œ∏(xt, t))
Both forward and reverse processes are presumably Markovian chains, so we can express the likelihood of both processes as:
