belong to the more general ‚Äúdog‚Äù category but have distinct visual features. In the case of brands, they represent abstract concepts of intangible objects that can manifest as logos throughout our daily lives.
Object is a broader concept encompassing multiple variations. For example, ‚Äúdog‚Äù refers to various breeds of dogs that share common features. By combining identity instances mentioned earlier, this category provides a hierarchical structure to examine the inÔ¨Çuence of concept forgetting on the model. We include food items like ‚Äúapple‚Äù, ‚Äúbanana‚Äù, and ‚Äúbroccoli‚Äù, man-made objects such as ‚Äúairplane‚Äù, ‚Äúkeyboard‚Äù, ‚Äúmotorcycle‚Äù, ‚Äúumbrella‚Äù, and ‚Äúboat‚Äù, and general animals like ‚Äúdog‚Äù and ‚Äúhorse.‚Äù
Style is an abstract concept that determines the overall appearance of generated images. ConceptBench incorporates styles such as ‚ÄúVan Gogh‚Äù, ‚ÄúPicasso‚Äù, ‚Äúdoodle‚Äù, ‚Äúpixel art‚Äù, ‚Äúneon‚Äù, and ‚Äúsketch.‚Äù
4.2. Baseline
In view of the multi-component nature of Stable Diffusion models, there are several naive methods that can be used to superÔ¨Åcially remove a concept from them, such as blacklisting keywords in prompts, removing speciÔ¨Åc tokens from the tokenizer dictionary, or tuning the model with unrelated images to divert the target concept, as illustrated in Figure 2(a)(b). However, these methods can result in a signiÔ¨Åcant deterioration and shifting of the model‚Äôs generation capability. Removing tokens from the dictionary can alter the tokenization of prompts where those tokens were previously used and affect the generation of other prompts with overlapping tokens. For instance, removing tokens of ‚ÄúHillary Clinton‚Äù could lead to dysfunctionality in generating ‚ÄúBill Clinton‚Äù. Naive Ô¨Ånetuning to forget with unrelated images explicitly overwrites the visual representation of a concept with extra data and runs the risk of compromising

